      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        How a Brisbane Real Estate Agent Determines the Price Guide
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        The price guide is the first number buyers see. Understanding how it is set helps sellers evaluate the advice they receive and ask the right questions before committing to a campaign.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>When a property is listed for sale in Brisbane, the agent publishes a price guide: a figure or range that tells buyers what the seller is broadly expecting to achieve. For sellers, this number matters more than it might initially seem. It shapes which buyers inspect, how competitive the open home attendance is, and ultimately how much urgency builds during the campaign. Getting the price guide right is one of the most consequential decisions in a real estate campaign, and it is worth understanding how the number is arrived at.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What the price guide actually is</h2>
      <p>The price guide is not a formal valuation. It is not the reserve price. It is the figure or range the agent publishes to attract the right pool of buyers. For private treaty campaigns, the guide is typically set at or near the asking price. For auction campaigns, it is usually set below the reserve, because the objective is to attract buyers who might compete and bid above it on auction day. Understanding this distinction matters: a price guide below what you expect to achieve is not necessarily a problem if the agent is running an auction and deliberately setting the guide to generate buyer competition.</p>

      <p>A formal bank valuation, by contrast, is produced by a licensed independent valuer engaged by a buyer's lender. It uses a different methodology and a different purpose. The price guide and the bank valuation are separate assessments that sometimes produce different numbers, and a gap between them does not automatically mean one is wrong.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The comparable sales method</h2>
      <p>The foundation of any price guide is comparable sales analysis. The agent looks at properties that have recently sold in the same suburb: same property type (house, townhouse, unit), similar land size, similar condition, and sold within the last three to six months. The more recent the sale, the more useful the data, because the Brisbane market can shift meaningfully across a six-month period.</p>

      <p>The agent then adjusts for the specific differences between each comparable and your property. A sold property two streets away on 600sqm that has a pool and a renovated kitchen is not a perfect comparable for a 450sqm property with original bathrooms, even if both are four-bedroom Queenslanders. The adjustments for those differences are where agent judgement matters most, and where a deep knowledge of the local market produces a more accurate guide than a purely algorithmic approach.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What makes a comparable truly comparable</h2>
      <p>The primary factors that determine whether a sale is a useful comparable are: bedroom and bathroom count, land area, position (corner block versus mid-block, street versus lane), car accommodation, renovation status, and proximity to amenities like schools, parks, and shopping. A three-bedroom cottage on 300sqm in a back lane is a poor comparable for a four-bedroom home on 600sqm fronting a quiet street, even if both are in the same suburb and sold in the same quarter.</p>

      <p>Agents with a deep transaction history in a suburb build an intuition for which adjustments matter most and by how much. An agent who has sold twenty homes in Norman Park develops an understanding of how much buyers in that market discount for a north-facing versus south-facing aspect, or how much a side access lane adds to land value for buyers who want room for a boat. That local knowledge is genuinely difficult to replicate from data alone.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The information problem: properties that did not sell</h2>
      <p>One limitation of relying solely on sold prices is that properties that did not sell are not on the public record. A property that was listed, attracted minimal interest, and was quietly withdrawn after eight weeks is not reflected in the comparable sales database. But that outcome is real market information. It tells you something about what buyers in that suburb were not willing to pay at that time, and for those property characteristics.</p>

      <p>Agents who are active in a suburb know what did not transact and why. They know which vendors took their property off the market, which ones accepted prices well below their initial expectations, and which campaigns failed because of overpricing rather than property quality. This information shapes a more accurate price guide than comparable sales data alone can produce. It is one of the clearest advantages an agent with a genuine local track record has over one who has simply run the numbers.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Adjusting for market movement</h2>
      <p>If comparable sales are three to six months old, the agent needs to assess whether the market has moved since those properties transacted. In a rising market, using older comparable sales without adjustment will produce a guide that understates current value. In a softening market, the same approach will produce a guide that overstates it.</p>

      <p>The adjustment is typically based on recent auction clearance rates, changes in days on market, and the volume and quality of buyer enquiry in the suburb. An agent tracking buyer enquiry week by week has a more current read on market direction than one relying solely on the historical sales record. In fast-moving markets, even a three-month-old comparable can understate current values significantly.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How method of sale shapes the price guide</h2>
      <p>Auction campaigns in Brisbane's inner east typically carry a price guide set below the seller's reserve. The rationale is to attract the widest possible field of interested buyers, including those who might not enquire if the guide was set at the reserve level. A broader buyer field creates the conditions for competitive bidding, which is how auction campaigns produce prices above reserve.</p>

      <p>Private treaty campaigns typically show a price at or near the asking price, because there is no auction mechanism to drive price above the listed figure. In a private treaty sale, the agent is negotiating one buyer at a time, and the listing price is effectively the ceiling from which negotiation begins. Setting a realistic asking price in a private treaty context is more critical than in an auction context, where the price guide is deliberately set to generate buyer interest rather than to reflect the expected final outcome.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Queensland law and underquoting</h2>
      <p>Queensland law requires agents not to advertise a property at a price they know is unrealistically low. The Office of Fair Trading monitors price guide compliance, and agents who consistently advertise properties well below the prices they achieve attract scrutiny. This is distinct from setting an auction guide below the reserve: a guide that reflects genuine buyer entry interest is not underquoting. A guide that is set artificially low to generate attendance or manufacture the appearance of competition is a different matter.</p>

      <p>For sellers, the practical implication is straightforward. An agent who recommends a campaign with a significantly lower price guide than your own expectation should be able to explain precisely why the guide is set where it is, which comparables support it, and how the campaign strategy is designed to achieve a price above the guide through buyer competition. That explanation should be specific, not vague reassurance.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What to ask your agent</h2>
      <p>When reviewing the price guide your agent recommends, three questions will tell you whether the work has been done properly. First: show me the three most comparable recent sales that support this guide. The agent should be able to name specific addresses, sale dates, and prices. Second: what adjustments have you made for the differences between those properties and mine, and why? The adjustments should be specific and defensible, not vague references to condition or location. Third: what is the highest price you genuinely believe this property can achieve under the right campaign conditions, and what has to go right for that to happen?</p>

      <p>The third question is the most revealing. An agent who answers it with a specific figure, a clear explanation of what buyer profile would pay that price, and an honest assessment of the campaign conditions required to attract that buyer is one who has thought carefully about the property and the market. An agent who deflects or gives only a range without reasoning has not done that work.</p>

